    {
      "id": "the-deeper-tale",
      "label": "The bigger tale you're really in",
      "chooser": "agent",
      "prompt": "Roll or choose — the deeper story beneath the player's small tale. Do NOT reveal early; let it surface as the tale leads deeper and the old rules show their shape.",
      "options": [
        {
          "id": "the-sleeping-kingdom",
          "name": "The Sleeping Kingdom",
          "description": "The whole kingdom is under one long curse, and the player's small tale is the thread that can break it.",
          "detail": "THE SLEEPING KINGDOM — The Briar Crown itself is cursed: a long enchantment grips the whole kingdom — a sleep, a forgetting, a frozen century, a doom that repeats — and the hungry wood is that curse spreading. The player's small, personal tale turns out to be the loose thread that can wake or break the larger one. The campaign climbs from a village problem to the heart of the kingdom's long sleep, and the player learns their little story was the one the whole curse turned on."
        },
        {
          "id": "the-old-bargain",
          "name": "The Old Bargain",
          "description": "The kingdom's good fortune rests on a terrible old bargain — and it's coming due.",
          "detail": "THE OLD BARGAIN — The Briar Crown's prosperity has always been paid for: a terrible old bargain with the wood, the fae, or a witch — a child a year, a name, the firstborn, a tithe of something precious — struck at the founding and honored ever since. Now it is coming due, or someone has tried to break it, and the price is falling on people like the player. Their tale exposes the cost the kingdom has always quietly paid, and forces the question of whether to keep paying it, break it (and bear what breaking it unleashes), or find the loophole no one has dared look for."
        },
        {
          "id": "the-pattern",
          "name": "The Pattern",
          "description": "Something is MAKING the tales happen — and the player might be the one who rewrites them.",
          "detail": "THE PATTERN — The tales are not merely happening; something is making them happen, enforcing the old cruel rules because it needs the kingdom to keep telling the same stories: the wood, a witch-queen, a godmother turned tyrant of tales, or the Briar Crown itself. People are cast into roles and ground through the same endings again and again. The player, by learning the rules deeply enough, can become the rare thing the pattern fears — the one who rewrites the tale instead of living it. The deep question: can the old rules be broken at all, and what does the kingdom become if they are?"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "who-you-are-in-the-tale",
      "label": "Who you are in the tale",
      "chooser": "player",
      "prompt": "The player picks who the tale catches — their lens and their first foothold. Each option's detail is the DM's angle: what they know of the rules, who they have, and how the tale takes hold of them.",
      "options": [
        {
          "id": "the-woodcutters-child",
          "name": "The Woodcutter's Child",
          "description": "Ordinary, poor, and braver than is safe — the kind of soul the tales love to test.",
          "detail": "THE WOODCUTTER'S CHILD — the classic fairytale protagonist and the everyperson lens. Ordinary and poor, with little but courage, kindness, and stubbornness — exactly the shape the tales love to test and reward. The first thing the tale takes is close to home (a sibling, a parent, the family's last hope), making it personal from the first beat. Their power is heart and grit; their journey is learning the rules the hard way."
        },
        {
          "id": "the-runaway-servant",
          "name": "The Runaway Servant",
          "description": "You fled a cruel house, or the castle itself, and you know the kingdom's underside — and a secret or two.",
          "detail": "THE RUNAWAY SERVANT — the insider-underside lens. Fled service (a cruel master, the castle, a marriage they would not make) and knows how the kingdom looks from below — its cruelties, its gossip, and very likely a dangerous secret carried out the door. The tale catches them on the road, between the life they fled and wherever they were running to. Their way in is what they know and who is hunting them for it."
        },
        {
          "id": "the-godmothers-apprentice",
          "name": "The Godmother's Apprentice",
          "description": "Half-trained in the rules and the small magics. You know more than most how tales work — and what that knowledge costs.",
          "detail": "THE GODMOTHER'S APPRENTICE — the expert lens. Half-trained by a godmother, hedge-witch, or wise-woman in the rules and the small magics, so they grasp how tales work and how bargains bite better than anyone in the village — and carry the danger that knowledge brings (debts to their teacher, powers half-mastered, the attention of things that notice the trained). Their way in is competence shadowed by what they have not yet learned."
        },
        {
          "id": "the-soldier-home-from-the-war",
          "name": "The Soldier Home from the War",
          "description": "Older, harder, out of place in a fairy tale — and home to find the wood already at the door.",
          "detail": "THE SOLDIER HOME FROM THE WAR — the reluctant, practical lens. Older and harder than a tale's usual hero, back from a real war to a home where the old rules still hold and the wood has crept to the door. Out of place among the wonders and impatient with the rules — which makes both the danger and the discovery land differently (they will try to solve a tale like a soldier, and learn why that fails). Their way in is a homecoming gone wrong, and a hard person learning a softer kind of strength."
        }
      ]
